n some cases possibly also Breton (mainly <b>Le Douget</b>): nickname for a man of respect, from the past participle of <i>doujañ</i> ‘to respect’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Docket","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably a shortened form of any of various German compound surnames beginning with <i>Docken-</i>, for example   Dockendorf  .","Altered form of Norwegian   Dokken  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dokken","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Jorgen, Arlis, Arnell, Erik, Hjalmer.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms so named, especially in southeastern Norway, from Old Norse <i>dǫkk</i> ‘hollow, depression’. Compare   Docken  ."]},{"name":"Dockendorf","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place near Bitburg called Dockendorf."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":41,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Andrew Doget Docket was born in 1414, in Grayrigg, Westmorland, England. He married Elizabeth Middleton on 1 January 1442. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 4 November 1484, at the age of 70, and was buried in Queen's College Chapel, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England."},"et":{"1414–4 Nov 1484":"1414–4. november 1484","1412–1485":"1412–1485","1454–1484":"1454–1484","1414–1484":"1414–1484","1414":"1414","1412":"1412","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1 Jan 1442":"1. jaanuar 1442","1485":"1485","4 Nov 1484":"4. november 1484","1484":"1484","from 1448 to 1484":"1448 kuni 1484","Grayrigg Manor, Grayrigg, Westmorland, England":"Grayrigg, Westmorland, England","Groton, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Queen's College Chapel, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Queen's College Chapel, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"1414–4 Nov 1484":"1414–4. marraskuuta 1484","1412–1485":"1412–1485","1454–1484":"1454–1484","1414–1484":"1414–1484","1414":"1414","1412":"1412","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1 Jan 1442":"1. tammikuuta 1442","1485":"1485","4 Nov 1484":"4. marraskuuta 1484","1484":"1484","from 1448 to 1484":"vuodesta 1448 vuoteen 1484","Grayrigg Manor, Grayrigg, Westmorland, England":"Grayrigg, Westmorland, England","Groton, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Queen's College Chapel, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Queen's College Chapel, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fr":{"1414–4 Nov 1484":"1414–4 novembre 1484","1412–1485":"1412–1485","1454–1484":"1454–1484","1414–1484":"1